>On 10/28/2012 04:12 PM, wolfbob wrote:
>> Maybe I don't understand (yet ...or is it again?)
>>
>> When I was in school (before spectrum analyzers) we had 
>Peak, RMS and 
>> average values for a signal in the voltage domain. With a voltage 
>> signal measured across a fixed resistor we found three values of 
>> power,  Peak Power (this is also a tough term as power is a 
>> steady-state parameter), RMS Power and Average Power. We were 
>> carefully taught that RMS power was the only one correctly defining 
>> the dissipation in the resistor. And yes the power was 
>determined by V^2/R.
>
>Certainly there are peak, RMS and average voltages, and 
>currents.  In a signal with time varying power the peak power 
>is the highest power in a particular time, that one's easy 
>(unless you get into the gory details). 
>  RMS and average are not though.  The power calculated from 
>an RMS voltage is an *average* power.  The use of the term 
>"RMS power" for this case is a misnomer.  As you said before 
>the RMS power is the only value that corresponds correctly to 
>dissipation in a resistor.  That means it corresponds to the 
>area under the V-I curve divided by time, and that value is an 
>average power.
>
>Electrical engineering textbooks are now very clear on this 
>point these days, it's unfortunate that RF textbooks aren't 
>always so clear.
>
>It's interesting to know that the problem was around before HP 
>and before spectrum analyzers.  I've always been told it was 
>all HP's fault.
>
>BR,
>Rob
